If you love cheese and are a wine connoisseur, this is a great place to expand your horizon.

So I had dinner this past July at Gary Danko for my birthday. Possibly the most-well known of the fine dining restaurants in SF, a culinary institution. Having seen the breadth of diversity and contrast this city has to offer in that regard, I wasn't sure what to expect. What we had on our three-course menu: Lobster Salad - with avocado, baby artichokes, roasted tomatoes, shaved fennel and mustard-tarragon vinaigrette. My app, quite good lobster. I think what surprised me most about it was the roasted tomato - the texture was almost meaty and provided a good base for the rest of the salad, which was a lot of fluffy frisee on top. Only wish that I was more adept at eating that or that it had been weighed down with something, as I tend to chase it about my plate. Soft-shelled Crab with Pickled Ginger, Lime and White Polenta - The highlight of the meal. There were bursts of lime with every bite of crisp, lightly fried crab as though it had been soaked in lime-scented water, nicely accented with bits of ginger. The polenta was just right in balancing the other stronger flavors. Wonderful. Moroccan Spiced Squab with Raisins, Almonds, Chermoula and Orange-cumin Carrots - I don't usually like Moroccan flavors (not a fan of mildly spiced sweet) but I was really curious about the stuffed squab. The meat was quite good, exceeded expectations, though the stuffing was so rich and filling that I had to have most of it to go. My birthday treat - a frozen lemon mousse cake with blueberries on top. Light, divine lemony sweetness that melted in your mouth, easily better than any cheesecake by a mile. I am not a dessert person but it was pure guilty satisfaction down to the last bite. We also had some cheeses and I enjoyed their cave aged Swiss gruyere immensely. Recommended for a special celebration.

As a special treat, my friend Ellen and I made a reservation for Gary Danko last week to celebrate the new year. We had a reservation for 9pm but got seated early since our table was already being held for us. Once we sat down we were offered a small appetizer, it appeared that each table was given different things, we ended up with a pate with some poached pears. Although the portion was just a little dollup, it was quite flavorful. For our meal we decided to pass on the special truffle tasting menu and decided to do the 3 course menu. Whats nice about the choose your own menu is that your not limited to just 1 appetizer, 1 entrée, or 1 dessert. If you want, you could order 3 meat dishes. Since my friend and I wanted to try everything, we decided to just split our dishes, so we ordered 1 appetizer, 2 seafood dishes, 2 meat dishes, and 1 dessert for our six choices. I think my favor one was the gulf shrimp risotto as well as the seared scallops with a sunchoke puree. The lobster was also good too. Overall my friend and I thought that the meat dishes were good but nothing too special. I think the duck breast and duck hash was better than the pork tenderloin with the pork belly. Lastly we finished off our meal with the butter cake which was really good. During dessert we were also given a dish of petifores which we boxed up for later. Also we were given a small pumkin muffin for the next day. Overall it was a great meal and I would definitely recommend this place to others. Service was excellent and as many other people have said, this place definitely deserves all the accolades.

I have been here 3 times and all 3 times I had different feelings about this place. Let me start with the service. The first time I went we sat at the bar because reservations were booked until 10pm. The service was wonderful and the bartender/server was extremely nice and accommodating. However, the second time I went I actually had reservations we sat at a table. It was the most horrible service ever. I felt so neglected and the only time the server came back was to deliver the food and take away the plates and asked if we wanted dessert. Other than that he ignored us completely. He would stop by the neighboring tables to check on them but completely pretended like we were nonexistent. Ok, now that I got that off my chest lets move on to the food! I was really impressed by their seared foie gras. The idea is to leave you wanting for more. The foie gras just melts in your mouth and that burst of flavor will remain. I suggest wine pairing if you do not have a favorite wine in mind because the wine menu can get overwhelming. I have tried the lobster, the filet, the pork belly, and a few other entrees but my favorite is the pork belly. It is the perfect balance of meat to fat ratio. A little bit tart, what's not to like? For cheese lovers try the cheese platter. Its fun and interactive because you get a little background of all of their cheeses and you pick out ones you would like to try. Platter served along with bread and grapes. Perfect with wine. Lastly, if you have room for desserts you have to try the baked chocolate soufflé. It is decadent and will leave you wanting A LOT more. If dessert is not your thing, you will still receive a sample platter of small delicate sweets as a complimentary dessert on the house. Finally, everyone leaves with a pastry (muffin) to take home and enjoy for the next morning. It is definitely a place to at least try if you live in or visit SF. Make sure you make reservation 3 months ahead of time if you want to dine Fri-Sun during normal dinner hours. Cheers!

We had the most enjoyable dinning experience at GD for a group of 10 last night. (4.5 ~ 5 stars). It was a celebration of several birthdays; the private room was cozy, warm, tastefully decorated with fresh flowers; perfect for the party. Our waitress was excellent; very knowledgeable, professional, good time management with a sense of humor. Service from beginning to end was impeccable. We took almost 3 hours to finish the dinner, never a dull moment; compare to some of the other $$$$ restaurants, GD is well worth the money. Half of us had 3 courses the other half had 4 (shared the dessert). We also had some champagne and cocktails plus 2 bottles of nicely aged Cabernet from home.(only 2 bottles allowed regardless of party size @$35/bottle corkage). All the dishes ranged from good to excellent, our favorites were Foie Fras (one of the best), Seafood risotto (good portion, very tasty), pork belly, bison, roasted lobster, crispy egg. Other great dishes were striped bass, duck, quail, crab salad and salmon. Only the scallops were kind of ordinary but still good. each time a new course came, 5 wait staff came in to serve all 10 dishes simultaneously, everything was nice and hot. The desserts were sooo good (chocolate souffle, butter cake, macaron ice cream sandwich); not too sweet at all which was a pleasant surprise. Because of the many birthdays we also received a complimentary whole chocolate mouse cake, it was so smooth and yummy, we almost finished the whole thing too. Each one was also given a nicely wrapped cake to take home, hubby had it for breakfast and said it was excellent. Gary Danko had certainly met our expectations, we will be back.

Best lobster risotto EVER! Food was great, service was good. Only thing I didn't like was that the tables are pretty close to one another. Both neighboring tables were couple that took way too many pictures of their dishes....one of them had the nerve to leave the flash on her SLR camera the whole time!

Reservations: They start taking reservations 2 months before your desired dining day. You should make one. You can either call in and talk to them directly, or you can go through their online system. Between the two, you should definitely call in. Phone call reservations get higher priority and better dining time options. People who reserve online usually get stuck with unpopular dining times (really early or late at night). Alternatively you can try your luck with no reservation at all if you have a small group (ie 2 people) and don't want to wait 2 months. They have a bar area that's available first come first serve. Experience: The service here is impeccable. I can easily say that it's the best I've experienced so far. We've dined at a few other Michelin restaurants, but this one takes the cake. Our water was refilled regularly, our server was both knowledgeable and personable, and there are little perks like an amuse bouche to start with, a little dessert sampler at the end of the meal, and a breakfast pastry to take home for the next day for all of the ladies (sorry dudes, you better hope your lady friend is willing to share). Added bonus is that the entire staff wears suits. It made me feel like I was having dinner served by the secret service (I don't think anyone else was imagining this though). Food: Food matters to me much more than service. At the end of the day, I remember places that served amazing food, and not too much about the service. While the food here was cooked to perfection and good, it wasn't quite the food orgasm with every course experience I was hoping it would be. You have the option of building yourself either a 3, 4, or 5 course menu. While the menu is divided into appetizers, entrees, and desserts, you don't have to build your meal that way. You can have all of your courses be entrees if you want, or do 1 appetizer and everything else desserts, or whatever combination you desire. I liked this flexibility. Portions were a bit smaller than I thought they would be. I couldn't imagine how anyone was going to finish a 5 course dinner on their own, and then I saw the portion size. I was expecting full dishes, but it's more like tapas portions. While this gives you the option to add a lot of variety, I was hoping to leave here stuffed given the price. My boyfriend and I were already planning a second dinner after our second course. We had the very popular roast Maine Lobster, herb crusted lamb, veal, and scallops. Of all of them, the scallops were the absolute best. I'm not even usually into scallops, but I was impressed with this dish. Lobster is really highly recommended on yelp, and while the puree was good, the lobster itself was not too exciting. I think they tried to keep it simple since lobster is a more expensive ingredient, but it just really lacked any notable flavor. Veal and lamb were also good, but I've had better at a lower price. The execution was flawless though. I finally experienced the much sought after food orgasm during dessert. I had the bananas flambe with vanilla ice cream and mascarpone filled crepes. I wished that dessert never ended. If I ever come back, I might just order 5 courses of that dessert. Price: A 3 course meal is $79, 4 courses is $96, and the 5 course is $114. Boyfriend and I had two 3 course menus, and the final bill post tax and tip came out around $206 for our party of two.

Gary Danko's offers a chef recommended tasting menu or you can build your own tasting menu from an incredible selection of over the top entrees. You don't have to order the same entrees as your date or the same number of entree's. You choose what entrees and how much you want to order.These guys get it.... they are customer focused, Some of our favorites are the lobster and mushroom risotto, the seared scallops, and the Thai seafood entree. If you enjoy Foie Gras you must order theirs. Gary Danko's continues to be our special occasion restaurant. We have been enjoyed this restaurant for the past 15 years. Kudos to the chef for the wide variety of exquisite entrees to choose from. The service staff is very polite, attentive and efficient,

Gary Danko is one best dining experiences in San Francisco. I've been three times and thoroughly enjoyed each visit. The service is amazing--engaging, expedient and highly knowledgeable. The food is wonderful. The chocolate souffle will be a memorable experience and the cheese course is inspired.

I've been here 4 times and it's this blast of awesome food, engagingly fun staff and enjoyable ambience. Hard to beat! Highly recommended

    So I had dinner this past July at Gary Danko for my birthday. Possibly the most-well known of the fine dining restaurants in SF, a culinary institution. Having seen the breadth of diversity and contrast this city has to offer in that regard, I wasn't sure what to expect.

    What we had on our three-course menu:

    Lobster Salad - with avocado, baby artichokes, roasted tomatoes, shaved fennel and mustard-tarragon vinaigrette. My app, quite good lobster. I think what surprised me most about it was the roasted tomato - the texture was almost meaty and provided a good base for the rest of the salad, which was a lot of fluffy frisee on top. Only wish that I was more adept at eating that or that it had been weighed down with something, as I tend to chase it about my plate.

    Soft-shelled Crab with Pickled Ginger, Lime and White Polenta - The highlight of the meal. There were bursts of lime with every bite of crisp, lightly fried crab as though it had been soaked in lime-scented water, nicely accented with bits of ginger. The polenta was just right in balancing the other stronger flavors. Wonderful.

    Moroccan Spiced Squab with Raisins, Almonds, Chermoula and Orange-cumin Carrots - I don't usually like Moroccan flavors (not a fan of mildly spiced sweet) but I was really curious about the stuffed squab. The meat was quite good, exceeded expectations, though the stuffing was so rich and filling that I had to have most of it to go.

    My birthday treat - a frozen lemon mousse cake with blueberries on top. Light, divine lemony sweetness that melted in your mouth, easily better than any cheesecake by a mile. I am not a dessert person but it was pure guilty satisfaction down to the last bite.

    We also had some cheeses and I enjoyed their cave aged Swiss gruyere immensely.

    Recommended for a special celebration.

    I have been here 3 times and all 3 times I had different feelings about this place.

    Let me start with the service. The first time I went we sat at the bar because reservations were booked until 10pm. The service was wonderful and the bartender/server was extremely nice and accommodating. However, the second time I went I actually had reservations we sat at a table. It was the most horrible service ever. I felt so neglected and the only time the server came back was to deliver the food and take away the plates and asked if we wanted dessert. Other than that he ignored us completely. He would stop by the neighboring tables to check on them but completely pretended like we were nonexistent.  

    Ok, now that I got that off my chest lets move on to the food!

    I was really impressed by their seared foie gras. The idea is to leave you wanting for more. The foie gras just melts in your mouth and that burst of flavor will remain.

    I suggest wine pairing if you do not have a favorite wine in mind because the wine menu can get overwhelming.

    I have tried the lobster, the filet, the pork belly, and a few other entrees but my favorite is the pork belly. It is the perfect balance of meat to fat ratio. A little bit tart, what's not to like?

    For cheese lovers try the cheese platter. Its fun and interactive because you get a little background of all of their cheeses and you pick out ones you would like to try. Platter served along with bread and grapes. Perfect with wine.

    Lastly, if you have room for desserts you have to try the baked chocolate soufflé. It is decadent and will leave you wanting A LOT more. If dessert is not your thing, you will still receive a sample platter of small delicate sweets as a complimentary dessert on the house.

    Finally, everyone leaves with a pastry (muffin) to take home and enjoy for the next morning.

    It is definitely a place to at least try if you live in or visit SF. Make sure you make reservation 3 months ahead of time if you want to dine Fri-Sun during normal dinner hours.

    Cheers!

    Pittsburg, CA
    264 friends

    Share review

    Embed review

    12/25/2014

    1 check-in

    Reservations: They start taking reservations 2 months before your desired dining day. You should make one. You can either call in and talk to them directly, or you can go through their online system. Between the two, you should definitely call in. Phone call reservations get higher priority and better dining time options. People who reserve online usually get stuck with unpopular dining times (really early or late at night). Alternatively you can try your luck with no reservation at all if you have a small group (ie 2 people) and don't want to wait 2 months. They have a bar area that's available first come first serve.

    Experience: The service here is impeccable. I can easily say that it's the best I've experienced so far. We've dined at a few other Michelin restaurants, but this one takes the cake. Our water was refilled regularly, our server was both knowledgeable and personable, and there are little perks like an amuse bouche to start with, a little dessert sampler at the end of the meal, and a breakfast pastry to take home for the next day for all of the ladies (sorry dudes, you better hope your lady friend is willing to share).  Added bonus is that the entire staff wears suits. It made me feel like I was having dinner served by the secret service (I don't think anyone else was imagining this though).

    Food: Food matters to me much more than service. At the end of the day, I remember places that served amazing food, and not too much about the service. While the food here was cooked to perfection and good, it wasn't quite the food orgasm with every course experience I was hoping it would be. You have the option of building yourself either a 3, 4, or 5 course menu. While the menu is divided into appetizers, entrees, and desserts, you don't have to build your meal that way. You can have all of your courses be entrees if you want, or do 1 appetizer and everything else desserts, or whatever combination you desire. I liked this flexibility. Portions were a bit smaller than I thought they would be. I couldn't imagine how anyone was going to finish a 5 course dinner on their own, and then I saw the portion size. I was expecting full dishes, but it's more like tapas portions. While this gives you the option to add a lot of variety, I was hoping to leave here stuffed given the price. My boyfriend and I were already planning a second dinner after our second course. We had the very popular roast Maine Lobster, herb crusted lamb, veal, and scallops. Of all of them, the scallops were the absolute best. I'm not even usually into scallops, but I was impressed with this dish. Lobster is really highly recommended on yelp, and while the puree was good, the lobster itself was not too exciting. I think they tried to keep it simple since lobster is a more expensive ingredient, but it just really lacked any notable flavor. Veal and lamb were also good, but I've had better at a lower price. The execution was flawless though. I finally experienced the much sought after food orgasm during dessert. I had the bananas flambe with vanilla ice cream and mascarpone filled crepes.  I wished that dessert never ended. If I ever come back, I might just order 5 courses of that dessert.

    Price: A 3 course meal is $79, 4 courses is $96, and the 5 course is $114. Boyfriend and I had two 3 course menus, and the final bill post tax and tip came out around $206 for our party of two.
